	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>blargg</b> [ Thu Dec 28, 2006 1:06 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It is not illegal to write an emulator, and it's debatable whether distribution is illegal. The patents on the NES technologies have expired, and an emulator doesn't contain any copyrighted code as the NES has no internal ROM (CIC excepted). There are hundreds of legally-distributable NES programs in the iNES format that can be run on a NES emulator.
<br />
<br />On the other hand, operating something without proper RF shielding can cause <em>actual</em> problems for other people, like interference with watching the daily mind-numbing content on television. Think of the couch potatoes!

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


